<DOC><DOCNO> AP880616-0232 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-PX-06-16-88 0035EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   06-16 0492</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0516</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Bank of New York Co. has sweetened its offer forrival Irving Bank Corp., slightly raising the stock portion of thebid and adding other shareholder incentives, including a specialcash dividend.   But some banking analysts on Wednesday predicted Irvingmanagement would continue snubbing its persistent suitor in favorof a friendly merger with Banca Commerciale Italiana SpA, Italy'ssecond-largest bank.   Bank of New York spokesman Owen Brady valued the revised bid forall of Irving's 18.5 million shares outstanding at around $1.4billion, about 25 percent higher than the existing hostile $1.1billion tender offer which remains in place.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An increasing number of insurance companiesare offering substantial premium discounts to the owners of carsequipped with air bags, the Transportation Department says.   Discounts for personal injury or medical premiums at 12 autoinsurance companies range from 15 percent to 60 percent on cars inwhich air bags protect the driver in a collision, the departmentsaid Wednesday.   It cautioned, however, that the discounts are not available inHawaii, Massachusetts, North Carolina, Texas, Illinois and Kentucky.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   International Business Machines Corp. isexpected to launch a major new family of mid-sized computers nextweek, and its nearest rival is preparing for a long, hard fight forcustomers.   Digital Equipment Corp., the world's No. 2 computer maker, sentexecutives to meet the press Wednesday and prepare the groundworkfor a response to the IBM computer family code-named Silverlake.   The skirmishing indicated the importance of next Tuesday'sannouncement to the vast midsection of the computer industry, themachines that fit in between personal computers and giantmainframes.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Campeau Corp. says it is getting out of thespecialty retailing business altogether and plans to sell theprofitable Ann Taylor division of its Allied Stores Corp.   ``We intend to focus our efforts and attention on the future ofour department store franchises,'' Allied chairman John W. BurdenIII stated Wednesday.   Campeau did not announce an asking price for the chain.</TEXT><DATELINE>KOUROU, French Guiana (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The European Space Agency has sentthree satellites into orbit on the first Ariane 4, a powerful newrocket it hopes will provide a competitive edge in the race tocommercialize space.   Officials of Arianespace, the agency's commercial arm,proclaimed Wednesday's inaugural launch ``a complete success.''</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market finished higher Wednesday, solidifying sharpgains posted in the previous session. The Dow Jones average of 30industrials, which jumped 25 points Tuesday, rose another 6.93points to close at 2,131.40, its second post-crash high in as manydays.   Bond prices declined on profit taking following a rally Tuesday.   The dollar closed narrowly mixed.   Grain and soybean prices shot up the daily maximum, whilelivestock and meat futures fell their limits as the droughtcontinued weighing heavily on the nation's commodities markets.</TEXT></DOC>